{"cursor":"6179","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Arguments for eternity' composed a particularly important area of philosophical\ndebate among Greek, Jewish, Islamic, and Christian philosophers during the\nancient and medieval periods. The foremost philosopher arguing for eternity was\nAristotle. Those subscribing to Creationism ex nihilo (that is, creation from\nnothing) challenged these arguments for eternity, and held instead that God\ncreated the universe, so that the universe had a definite beginning in time.\n","linknr":301,"url":"Arguments_for_eternity","recorded":1362581204,"links":19,"instances":["aristotle","physics","philosophy_of_time","religion"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Philosophical arguments"],"headings":["From the nature of the physical world","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Merge-arrows.svg/50px-Merge-arrows.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Wooden_hourglass_3.jpg/76px-Wooden_hourglass_3.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fd/Portal-puzzle.svg/16px-Portal-puzzle.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["metaphysics","aristotle"],["motion","physics"],["transcendence","religion"],["eternalism","philosophy_of_time"]],"members":["metaphysics","motion","eternalism","transcendence"],"related":["Greece","Jew","Islam","Christian","Philosopher","Ancient_history","Middle_Ages","Aristotle","Creationism","Ex_nihilo","Argument","Eternity","God","Universe","Matter","Existence","Hypokeimenon","Inductive_reasoning","Observation","Metaphysics_(Aristotle)","Maimonides","Empiricism","Avicenna","Logical_possibility","Necessary_truth","Motion_(physics)","